					.combinatorial__text 
						h2 Combinatorial Psychology
						p.combinatorial__text-one is a proprietary method of psychological analysis developed concurrently in Germany, the United States and the United Kingdom in the latter part of the 20th century. The earliest advocates of the method include the inventor of electroencephalography (EEG) which has today become neuroscience, Professor W. Grey Walter of the Burden Neurological Insitute at Bristol.
						p.combinatorial__text-two Other proponents for this have included two Nobel Prize Winners in the fields of biology and chemistry, Dr. Konrad Lorenz and Dr. Niko Tinbergen. As a young student I was mentored and trained in this method of analysis and have been using it for many years to solve my own problems and those of others. This extensive method can be used to solve a range of issues both strategic, for example in business and emotional when applied to relationships and individual interests.
